About the Business

Established in 2014. Traditional Greek street-food with a twist. Nick the Greek Souvlaki and Gyro House offers a modern variety to age old delicacies. Multi-generation Greek restauranteurs Nick, Nick and yes Nick opened their first store in 2014, and quickly ballooned to 8 location in the Bay Area in just 5 years! At Nick the Greek our number 1 priority is blending the freshest ingredients and authentic Greek recipes into a flavor profile that is truly irresistible. Our food quality and low price points keep your pallet and your wallet happy while our 5 star services keeps you relaxed and able to enjoy our modern ambiance. Nick the Greeks menu pairs family favorites like; gyros, souvlaki and baklava with our loaded Greek fries, bifteki burger and 'Greek style' frozen yogurt. Come see what all the buzz is about and maybe you'll want to be a Nick just like us!…

    I hadn't been to a restaurant since COVID had started, so I was excited when we had the opportunity to visit for dinner.  Our friend had invited us to the grand opening!  

    On my drive into the lot, we were greeted by huge bouquet of blue and white balloons.  The patio was open with a few patrons eating and talking merrily.  The operations inside seemed to hum, with a sizable staff ready to serve up orders for the line of customers standing 6 feet apart outside.  

    My wife and I split a Beef/Lamb Gyro Pita and a Pork Souvlaki Plate (which is basically what I know as kebabs).  The gyro meat was soft and flavorful, and the pork tender and juicy.  Of the four sauces (tzatziki, hummus, spicy ketchup and one other), our favorite hands-down was the tzatziki -- it made me think of fancy hotel cucumber water and tart yogurt.  Of note, the spicy ketchup is more spicy (of the peppery variety) than I had expected, and it caught me off guard!  The portions were plenty and we were full after our meal, and would have been fuller still if we hadn't dropped one of the two souvlaki skewers.  Our puppy got to enjoy it for his dinner, though!  

    Speaking of dogs, seating is outdoors only, and dogs are allowed.  We spotted another poodle, and our puppy wouldn't stop barking, so we had to put him away in the car.

    Overall, our bellies were satisfied, and we had a nice time eating outdoors.  We'd visit again, but because we live in Los Gatos, Dublin is a far drive for us.  We'd need to visit one of the other locations closer to us (maybe Santa Clara, or Sunnyvale).  With some heat lamps, which I was assured were coming soon, I think the experience would have been perfect!  What a nice night to have eaten out!

    Our puppy loves souvlaki, too!

    We came here for a Friday night take out dinner. We wanted to come and try out this new place after seeing a really busy grand opening and reviewing the Yelp comments as well as positive feedback from a friend of ours.

    The restaurant is well staffed for speedy in and out take out.  It is set up as a fast casual order and pick up. The menu is quite typical of a Mediterranean Greek restaurant with a variety of pita, combo dishes and salads. I like how they are a variety of protein options including the typical beef and lamb, chicken, and veggie in addition to pork belly and pork souvlaki.

    From the time we arrived to placing the order to waiting for our food to be prepared, we probably were in and out within 10 to 15 minutes. Service was friendly as well.   There was plenty of space indoors to wait socially distance, and you can even tell from the picture that a customer brought in a shopping cart from a nearby grocery store!

    We ordered beef and lamb gyro pitas and a pork belly pita. They were well packed that by the time we got home the meals were still intact and ready to be devoured.   Aside from needing a quick warm-up in the microwave, the food was fresh and delicious.  The meats were full of flavor, but maybe a little bit salty as I found myself drinking a lot of water throughout the night afterwards.   This definitely would rate somewhere between some of the fast food like Greek restaurants and some of the more pricier ones nearby. One thing to note that I really liked was that the meats were authentically cut from the spinning rotisserie and having previously traveled to Greece before the pitas were stuffed with french fries as they should be!

    The only thing that can make this better is looking forward to when dining out is safe again and I could enjoy my food fresh from the kitchen!

  • Shayla B.

    Elite '2021

    Nick the Greek has hit the tri-valley and it's tasting mighty fine! SO excited that this fast casual Mediterranean food chain is starting to migrate into the East Bay! I first tried Nick the Greek about 5 or 6 years ago when I was hanging out in Downtown San Jose. Loved it then and I'm happy to report that I'm still lovin' it now.

    This location is housed in the busy Persimmon Place shopping center right next door to Koja Kitchen. Parking can be tough but it's still doable. They had their cute patio space open for outdoor dining, and there were a few groups taking advantage of it on a warm Saturday afternoon. The process is simple; you walk in and wait in line, order at the register, and then they'll call your order when everything is ready.

    I was in the mood for gyro, so I decided to order the beef and lamb gyro pita sandwich and made it a meal with Greek fries and a drink. Service at the counter was fast, friendly, and courteous. The young lady at the register informed me that they had only been open for a week and that it had been extremely busy since they're grand opening. Always nice to hear that a new business is thriving. It didn't take too long before my food was ready. I've gotta say, I absolutely adore the packaging. Not only are their to-go boxes adorable, they're sturdier than your average paper bag and way more eco-friendly than a plastic bag. Plus, I love how they laid everything down in the box. You can tell that they didn't rush to put it together. I know that most people won't even care about that, but I hate when places just throw your food into the bag. An A+ for packaging and handling here for sure.

    Now onto the food; it was so yummy and filling. I took it to a park down the street and had a solo lunch picnic (my newest COVID obsession). The gyro was loaded with nice meaty pieces of beef and lamb. The meat was so tender and flavorful. The only thing that I don't really care for is that they add fries to the gyro. I actually asked them not to add the fries, but they did anyways. It's no biggie because they can be easily be removed, but fries in the gyro sandwich and fries on the side just seem like overkill. I honestly could have just had the gyro all by itself and it would have been enough for me, but I couldn't come here without getting those Greek fries! Feta on fries is just one lovely little creation that I can't say no to. Between the huge gyro sandwich and all of those fries, my belly damn near exploded while I was at the park. I left there stuffed and ready for a nap!

    I just found out that Nick the Greek is opening a location in the Veranda soon which is even closer to me than this location in Dublin. So happy to have them as a convenient option now when I'm craving for some fast Greek food eats.

    See all photos from Shayla B. for Nick the Greek

    Stopped in for the grand opening. We got the pork souvlaki plate and a beef/lamb gyro plate ($13.95 ea). Although the food was free today, I would say that the pricing is reasonable. I am posting a photo of the entire menu here too.

    How was the food? Pretty darn good. The meat was seasoned and cooked just right. The tzatziki sauce had a hint of lemon in it, which was still quite pleasant. They also offered a spicy sauce that is not too spicy, the right level in my opinion. The side salad is a spot on Greek salad. No matter what you order, I'd recommend getting a side salad with it.

    Return? Absolutely! This is going on my favorites list.

    Solid new spot between the Koja Kitchen and the chipotle (It replaced the Yalla Mediterranean spot). We decided to try this place for dinner since it was new and we look Greek/Mediterranean food!   We ordered a plate, a bowl, a kids plate, the Greek fries, and the Greek salad. They offered a large menu, various salads, and a few dessert options that looked yummy too.

    We ordered and waited for a while, and I watched as our food sat on the counter for sometime. They called 4 numbers after ours and hubby had to ask them for our food. The portions are huge, prices are reasonably, we paid $9.95 for a salad without dressing and that was a bit disappointing. The fries were huge though, but the gyro meet was super dry. I found myself wanting the replace the dry bowl of meat and rice with sauce. Their spicy yogurt sauce is a bit mild for my taste and the only other option was sriracha (so this place is perfect if you don't like spicy sauces). I found myself wishing for a more chili based sauce like the sauce from the Kebab Shop. Overall not bad, we only tried the beef/lamb combo, they were sold out of the pork by the time we got there.

    They have a lot of COVID practices in place, most of the staff were wearing their masks properly, some wore gloves and they had hand sanitizer available. The place seemed busy, not sure what happened with our order that we had to wait a lot longer than most but not too big of deal. Just not ideal to wait so long indoors during COVID times, maybe I'll look for delivery options next time. We're so lucky to have so many Greek options and this place is close so maybe we will be back!
